text_answer.content: The only reason I gave a "No" answer for suitability of the writing prompt is that many 6th graders may not have a personal narrative to write about as an individual enterprise, such as the one noted in the passage. I think the prompt should include "including participation in a group." Additionally, I think it needs to be stated (and moved up) in the second passage that permission had been sought and granted before the students began painting in the neighborhood on public and private property. It could be addressed by Charlotte noting she had asked and been granted permission by one business owner before she started her project, and that she and Mason followed up accordingly with other business owners.

text_answer.content: I find the idea of students sneaking into the library to meet at midnight, past a sleeping guard objectionable. Students are impressionable, and presenting this scenario as acceptable (even laudable) behavior obscures the good the fictional account is meaning to present. With some tweaks, the club could meet at 5:00 at a nearby park or some such and still have the same effect. The mind map should be presented as twin sets of boxes since the instructions detail there should be 4 events for each passage in chronological order. This would make teacher grading much easier, as well, if formatted in an organized manner.
